<h1 class="post_region_title" data-pats="question_title_text">Overview and Goals:</h1>
<p class="p1"><span class="s1">This is an undergrad/graduate level course in computer networking. The </span><span class="s1">emphasis will be on the basic performance and engineering </span><span class="s1">tradeoffs in the design and implementation of computer networks, with a focus on the </span><span class="s1">Internet. The second half of the course includes several classic and recent research papers, which cover </span><span class="s1">some important problems in networking. </span></p>
<p class="p1"><span class="s1">The goal is for students to learn not only how the Internet works<span class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp; </span>today, but also the rationale behind its </span><span class="s1">design and how it is likely to evolve in the future. The class includes multiple hands-on </span><span class="s1">programming assignments/written assignments and an open ended project.&nbsp;</span></p>
<p class="p1"><span class="s1">Topics to be covered include: networked applications (e.g., web, p2p), reliability, congestion and flow control, </span><span class="s1">routing, addressing, naming, wireless, and new Internet architectures.</span></p>
